Question:Count how many times each word appears.
Input:
List<String> data = Arrays.asList("a", "b", "a", "c", "b", "a");

Solutions:-

Java 8 Streams count word occurrences using Collectors.groupingBy with Collectors.counting(). For input ["a", "b", "a", "c", "b", "a"], produces {"a"=3, "b"=2, "c"=1}.

#Step-by-Step Logic
Stream words → groupingBy(Function.identity(), counting()) → Map<String, Long> frequency map.

#Complete Implementation

import java.util.Arrays;
import java.util.List;
import java.util.Map;
import java.util.function.Function;
import java.util.stream.Collectors;

public class WordFrequency {
    public static Map<String, Long> countWords(List<String> data) {
        return data.stream()
                   .collect(Collectors.groupingBy(
                       Function.identity(),
                       Collectors.counting()
                   ));
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        List<String> data = Arrays.asList("a", "b", "a", "c", "b", "a");
        Map<String, Long> frequencies = countWords(data);
        System.out.println(frequencies);  // {a=3, b=2, c=1}
    }
}

#Thought Process
groupingBy(identity, counting) creates frequency map in single pass. Function.identity() uses word itself as key. counting() downstream collector returns Long. O(n) time, HashMap storage.

#Edge Cases Analysis
Empty list: Empty Map.
Single word: {word=1L}.
All duplicates: {word=n}.
Null list: NPE on stream().
Null elements: Groups null if multiple (null=count).
Empty strings: {""=count}.

